FT  02 SEP 92 / UK Company News: Burns-Anderson offshoot in buy-out plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The management of Burns-Anderson Independent Network, a 75.1 per cent owned
subsidiary of Burns-Anderson Group, the recruitment and financial services
operation that went into administration receivership two weeks ago, is
staging a buy-out.
Agreement in principle has been reached with Touche Ross, the
administrators.
Burns-Anderson Independent Network, the third largest network of financial
advisers in the country, is financially ring-fenced from its parent. It owns
24.9 per cent of the capital and is putting together a deal to buy out the
rest. Mr Alan Taylor, managing director of the network, which has 375
individually registered members with Fimbra, the self-regulatory
organisation, said he was hopeful the price would be satisfactory to all
parties. The network made pre-tax profits of Pounds 15,000 to Pounds 20,000
in 1991 on turnover of Pounds 13m to Pounds 14m.
Investors Planning Associates, another company in the Burns-Anderson stable,
said it, too, was putting together a management buy-out. 'We're fed up with
people owning us who did nothing for us,' the company said. IPA, which has
57 Fimbra-registered individuals, said pre-tax profits amounted to less than
Pounds 100,000 in 1991 on turnover of Pounds 2.4m.
</TEXT>
