<HEADLINE>
FT  02 SEP 92 / Observer: Discounting
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir Tom Cowie's failure to win control of rival motor dealer Henlys in a
hard fought Pounds 32m bid could be put down to the fall in the stock market
or sympathy for the under-dog on the part of Henlys' shareholders. But
perhaps his choice of advisers played a part.
Sunderland-based Cowie employed Noble Grossart, the Edinburgh merchant bank,
and Dickinson Dees, a Newcastle-based lawyer. It brought in an external PR
firm halfway through the campaign. It estimates its costs at around Pounds
600,000 to Pounds 650,000 - 'we drive a hard bargain' boasts Gordon Hodgson,
Cowie's chief executive.
Henlys fees, by contrast, are in the Pounds 850,000 to Pounds 900,000
region. But then that may not be such a high price to pay if it helps secure
the firm's continued independence.
</TEXT>
