<HEADLINE>
FT  02 SEP 92 / Protests grow as big four review bankcharges
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONSUMERS' organisations and opposition politicians yesterday expressed
alarm at the possible introduction of new current account charges by the
high street banks. They warned that the banks would face serious
consequences if they acted together to make customers pay more.
None of the high street clearers would admit to having plans to end free
banking (if the customer remains in credit) in the near future, but all of
the big four high street banks said they were reviewing the situation.
Smaller banks indicated that they were less likely to introduce new current
account fees than the larger clearers. Royal Bank of Scotland, the fifth
largest UK bank, said it would not be ending free-if-in-credit banking for
its customers in the foreseeable future.
'Frankly we are amazed. The banks ought to be trying to get their costs down
by reducing their bad debts rather than by charging customers more,' an RBS
spokesman said.
At Westminster the Labour party yesterday stepped up the political pressure
on the banks not to raise charges in concert - and on the government to
intervene if they tried to do so - with a letter to Mr Norman Lamont, the
chancellor, calling for an in-depth inquiry into banks' costs, charges and
services.
Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, argued there is a strong case for a
statutory code of practice instead of reliance on self-regulation.
He said: 'Customers - already facing rising charges in the last year - can
ill afford to pay more, especially when many charges are deducted without
prior billing and often the increased charges are not properly explained.'
The Office of Fair Trading, which last year accused high street banks of
being high handed and insensitive, said it would be watching carefully to
see whether the banks act in unison when introducing charges.
If new current account charges are introduced, the OFT would expect the
banks to provide their customers with full notification of the changes at an
early date. However, the move would not necessarily mean an automatic
investigation leading to referral to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission.
Ms Jean Eaglesham of the Consumers Association, which also expressed fears
that the banks may jointly introduce charges, said: 'Whichever bank moves
first must expect to lose a vast number of its customers so our message to
the public is that if your bank brings in charges, then switch to another
one.'
Mr John Wriglesworth of UBS Phillips &amp; Drew, a leading building society
specialist, said he believed building societies would benefit if banks
introduced new charges. He said: 'The high street banks are simply trying to
make the consumer pay for the money they lent to Robert Maxwell and their
other bad debts.'
Editorial Comment, Page 12
