FT  02 SEP 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Thank goodness for BBC2. Even if the channel seems to be as besotted with
the US as every other network in Britain, at least it still presents fresh
and, quite often, intelligent programmes. While BBC1, ITV and Channel 4
concentrate on soap operas, embarrassing game shows with Anneka Rice and
repeats, BBC2 is offering all sorts of different material.
The Shetland Sessions (7.40) is the first in a series featuring local and
international folk musicians recorded at the 1991 Shetland Folk Festival. At
8.10 the channel begins a three-part 'Timewatch' special on McCarthyism: The
Un-Americans. With the cold war over, this is said to be the first
investigation to concentrate not on the famous Hollywood targets but on
ordinary men and women who were persecuted for supposed communist
sympathies.
Today's 'ScreenPlay' (9.00) is David Edgar's first original television
drama, Buying A Landslide. The title is a reference to Joseph P. Kennedy's
reported statement that he was happy to buy an election for John Kennedy
'but not a landslide'. Edinburgh Nights (11.15) pays tribute to the man who
made the National Film And Television School what it is, Colin Young.
