<HEADLINE>
FT  02 SEP 92 / Reform of public services 'flawed'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government's campaign to improve public services has been seriously
undermined by weaknesses in its systems for measuring value for money,
according to Mr Howard Davies, director-general of the Confederation of
British Industry.
Mr Davies, a former head of the Audit Commission, the public spending
watchdog, praises the government's record on reforming schools and the
National Health Service in a pamphlet issued yesterday by the Social Market
Foundation, an independent think tank.
He says, however, that the drive for better quality in public services is
impeded by the Treasury's twin roles of controlling spending and promoting
value for money.
Until June Mr Davies was controller of the commission, where he was at the
forefront of the government's drive for greater efficiency in local
government and the National Health Service.
Mr Davies recommends strengthening the Cabinet Office efficiency unit to
promote value for money and extend the use of market mechanisms to improve
quality of services.
Fighting Leviathan. Social Market Foundation, 20 Queen Anne's Gate, London
SW1H 9AA. Pounds 6.
