<HEADLINE>
FT  02 SEP 92 / Tokyo bribery scandal claims leading politician
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AN INFLUENTIAL Japanese politician, Mr Kiyoshi Kaneko, the governor of
Niigata prefecture, resigned yesterday, prompting the country to wonder who
will be the next to fall in a scandal over alleged bribes by a parcel
delivery company.
The resignation followed a confession last week by Mr Shin Kanemaru, vice
chairman of the ruling Liberal Democratic party, that his political
secretary had received Y500m (Pounds 2m) from Tokyo Sagawa Kyukyo, a parcel
company.
Mr Kanemaru stepped down as party vice chairman and said he would resign as
leader of the LDP's largest faction, though the faction's members voted
unanimously on Monday for him to retain that post 'to prevent confusion in
the party'.
The downfall of Mr Kaneko, aged 60, apparently came after a tap on the
shoulder from Japanese prosecutors investigating Tokyo Sagawa, alleged to be
behind Y500bn in illegal payments to senior politicians. Money was donated
to win friends in high places, and prosecutors suspect that legislative
favours were sought by the rapidly expanding company.
Mr Kaneko has denied illegally receiving Sagawa donations to support his
1989 election, though his campaign workers have admitted taking at least
Y100m and Japanese newspapers suggest that his office received Y300m. The
governor said it is 'not appropriate' to comment on the allegations until
the investigation is completed.
'For several days, I contemplated my future actions and decided to take
political, ethical and all responsibilities for the confusion incurred in
prefectural politics,' Mr Kaneko told prefectural officials in Niigata, on
the western coast of Japan.
Under the Political Funds Control Law, an individual can donate a maximum of
Y1.5m to a politician, while companies capitalised at more than Y105bn are
permitted to donate as much as Y100m to a party or politician over a year.
Mr Kaneko's resignation is another stain on the LDP, as he was supported by
the ruling party and had frequent contact with Mr Kanemaru, regarded as the
party's power-broker because of his ability to raise campaign cash.
Tokyo Sagawa was able to cultivate ties with senior politicians because of
the enormous cost of Japanese political campaigns, and lists are circulating
in Nagatacho, Tokyo's political district, naming a dozen politicians said to
be under investigation for receiving Sagawa money.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 3
</PAGE>
