<HEADLINE>
FT  02 SEP 92 / Company 'green' reports criticised
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FEWER THAN half the companies mentioning environmental issues in their
annual reports are providing information of much value, according to Company
Reporting, the Edinburgh-based monthly monitoring service.
In a sample of 570 company reports 23 per cent address environmental
matters, compared with 10 per cent in a survey in July last year.
But 12 per cent of the sample contained statements which are 'usually vague
or meaningless, lacking any real information content', Company Reporting
says.
Nine per cent of companies disclosed specific details on their environmental
policies, compared with 5 per cent in the previous survey. Even among those
providing this information, there was wide variation in the level of detail.
Only three companies - Imperial Chemical Industries, RTZ and Thames Water -
disclosed the costs of environmental protection measures adopted.
An environmental audit - in which the company's performance was
independently scrutinised - was mentioned by 3 per cent of companies, but
none gave details of the results or measures taken to address issues raised
by the audits.
Company Reporting says Ford and Grand Metropolitan are among the better
examples of reports giving information on 'green' issues. It highlights
statements by BAT, British Airways, Hanson and Allied Lyons as 'of little
value'. In a separate analysis, Company Reporting notes that 19 per cent of
companies publish a statement of corporate objectives.
Company Reporting. 68 Dundas Street, Edinburgh EH3 6QZ. Subscription Pounds
315 a year.
</TEXT>
