<HEADLINE>
FT  02 SEP 92 / Bulgaria to resume paying debt interest
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SOFIA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BULGARIA WILL start paying off overdue interest on its Dollars 12bn foreign
debt on September 15, ending a break of more than two years in debt
repayments, Mr Ivan Kostov, finance minister, said yesterday, Reuter reports
from Sofia. 'The first payment will be 25 per cent of Bulgaria's overdue
interest,' he said.
Bulgaria's last communist government suspended payments of principal on
foreign debt in March 1990 and froze interest payments in June of that year.
The country owes Dollars 10bn to more than 300 commercial banks and Dollars
2bn to the Paris Club of official creditors.
Mr Kostov said Bulgaria would pay Dollars 10m each month but did not specify
how the money would be shared between the commercial banks and official
creditors. He also said further negotiations with the London Club of
commercial creditors had been set for October 5.
The start of payments would not affect the exchange rate between the
Bulgarian lev and the dollar on the Bulgarian currency market, where daily
turnover is around Dollars 40m.
Last month, Mr Kostov called on the Bulgarian central bank to scale down its
dollar buying on the foreign exchange market in a move interpreted by
economists as an attempt to boost the lev to make dollar-denominated debt
repayments cheaper. But the bank countered by saying that the lev had
strengthened against the dollar and that the currency had achieved internal
convertibility.
</TEXT>
