<HEADLINE>
FT  01 SEP 92 / TUC looks at impact of Japanese
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANY Japanese companies in the UK are more willing to work with trade unions
than are British employers, according to Mr John Monks, TUC deputy general
secretary.
Mr Monks says in an article in Personnel Management magazine that while UK
companies have derecognised unions many Japanese companies have recognition
agreements with TUC affiliates.
He says it is too early to assess the impact of Japanese companies on
industrial relations in Britain. Some Japanese production and personnel
systems appeal to British unions, particularly skill-building, abolishing
status distinctions, emphasising quality and pushing creativity and
responsibility to the shopfloor.
On the negative side he points to disparity of pay between lead companies
and subcontractors, the treatment of women workers and the lack of
independent status for unions outside a company. Accusations of social
control are equally worrying, he adds
Mr Monks says Britain is the largest recipient of Japanese inward investment
in Europe and the TUC is studying Japanese labour relations. UK companies
had to respond to the challenge of meeting Japanese efficiency standards.
Super-unions will erode the identity of union members with strong industrial
traditions or special professional interests, according to Mr Roger Lyons,
leader of the MSF technical and professional union. His statement follows
the announcement that talks about a possible merger are to be held by the
GMB and TGWU general unions.
Mr Lyons urged unions to concentrate on individual services to members,
although he admitted the 600,000-strong MSF, itself the product of a merger
between ASTMS and TASS in 1988, had learned 'the hard way'.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-5351</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CICBJAEDFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920901
