<HEADLINE>
FT  01 SEP 92 / Foreign Exchanges and Money Markets: Strains in the ERM
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DOLLAR'S weakness will continue to preoccupy dealers this week, but the
strains in the exchange rate mechanism are now of the first importance in
Europe, writes James Blitz.
At the end of last week, the instability in the ERM was acute. The D-Mark,
which should ideally be at the centre of the European Monetary System's
grid, was at the top, pushing several currencies towards the bottom of their
bands. The Italian lira breached its ERM floor against the D-Mark several
times.
There are three possible courses of action to combat the crisis: Central
banks could continue to intervene to support sterling and the Italian lira.
'Such intervention will buy time,' said Mr Gerard Lyons, chief economist at
DKB International in London, 'but it will require a change in economic
fundamentals to fully work.'
The second possibility is a raising of interest rates by countries with the
weaker currencies. 'This is the least desirable option and is likely to be
the most counter-productive,' added Mr Lyons. In the UK's case an increase
in interest rates will give a better return to sterling investors, but would
worsen perceptions of Britain's economic plight.
Thirdly, Germany could reduce interest rates or revalue the D-Mark. Although
the German economy is slowing, there is little sign that the Bundesbank will
cut rates before the year's end.
A realignment still seems the best way out of the problem. The traditional
obstacle here has been French intransigence because a weaker franc will
upset their good record on inflation. But after last week's debacle, the
franc is less than 3 centimes off its floor against the D-Mark. Faced with
the prospect of raising rates, the French may give way on realignment, after
all.
</TEXT>
