<HEADLINE>
FT  01 SEP 92 / Fresh row looms over pension funds: Lucas pensioners seek
return of surplus; British Rail must repay Pounds 25m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TRACY CORRIGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LUCAS Industries and British Rail have come under fire for their handling of
pension fund surpluses.
Pensioners of Lucas Industries have issued a High Court writ against the
trustees of the fund, seeking the return of Pounds 150m transferred to the
company last November, while British Rail has been ordered to repay Pounds
25m, which it had clawed back from its pension fund.
Both organisations took advantage of the 1988 Income and Corporation Taxes
Act, which says if pension fund assets exceed its liabilities by more than 5
per cent it must reduce the surplus or lose its tax-exempt status.
The question of who owns any pension fund surplus - generally created by
heavy investment in the late 1970s followed by booming stock markets in the
1980s - has become increasingly contentious in the wake of the Maxwell
scandal. Pensioners feel entitled to some of the money, since it is a form
of deferred pay consisting partly of their contributions.
However, companies can argue that since they effectively underwrite any
potential deficiency, they should benefit from any surplus.
The legal change in 1988 allowed Lucas pension fund trustees to change the
deeds so some of the surplus could be transferred to the company, said a
spokesman for Lucas.
The payment of Pounds 150m to Lucas Industries - reduced to Pounds 90m after
40 per cent tax was levied - was approved last November by the Occupational
Pensions Board. The transfer allowed the company to announce profits for the
six months to January of Pounds 90.2m and an interim dividend of 2.1p.
At the time of the transfer, the pension fund had assets valued at Pounds
1.7bn, with a Pounds 600m surplus, now reduced to Pounds 225m.
According to a spokesman for Lucas Industries, the trustees acted 'with the
support of the trade unions and the vast majority of employees and
pensioners.'
But Mr Douglas Taylor and 69 other beneficiaries of the fund have issued a
summons against Lucas Pensions Trust (the trustees), asking the High Court
to decide whether the trustees in fact acted lawfully.
British Rail's accounts in 1992-1993 will include an exceptional item of
Pounds 25m, which it has to repay to its Pounds 7bn pension fund.
At its last pension fund review in 1990, British Rail decided to begin a
contribution holiday for the company and staff. When the decision was
implemented in September 1991, the holiday was backdated to the start of the
financial year in April 1991. In fact, such a claw-back is not allowed under
trust law, according to a British Rail spokesman.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
