<HEADLINE>
FT  01 SEP 92 / MPs warn against collusion over bank charges
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE POSSIBILITY of an agreement among the big four high street banks to
phase out free banking was greeted with warnings yesterday from MPs across
the House of Commons against possible collusion.
Mr John Watts, the Tory chairman of the all-party Treasury committee of MPs,
expressed unease at the idea of more extensive charges being introduced in
concerted action by the banks.
Recalling the committee's inquiry into the banks' relationship with small
business customers, he said that if there were widespread moves to introduce
new charges, the MPs might well want to look at the matter.
'It is certainly potentially a topic we might want to look at if there were
a substantial change in the basis of banks' charges.'
His remarks came as Barclays, the biggest UK high street bank, confirmed
that plans to reintro- duce charges for many current account holders were
'on the agenda'. The other three main banks also indicated over the weekend
that they were considering similar steps.
Mr Nigel Griffiths, Labour's consumer affairs spokesman, has already written
to the Office of Fair Trading asking it to investigate whether there was
collusion against the public interest in the banks' plans.
Although Barclays, which has 6.5m current account holders, has no plans 'at
the moment' to introduce charges on accounts in credit, an official said 'we
are conscious that there is an imbalance between the 80 per cent who pay no
current account charges and those that are overdrawn'.
Over the weekend Mr Brian Pearse, chief executive of Midland Bank, said
there was no point in providing current account holders who never paid
charges with a service.
'Over time, hopefully, we'll persuade our customers you don't get anything
for nothing,' Mr Pearse said.
Midland has 4.5m current account customers, of which two-thirds do not pay
charges. A Midland official said yesterday that Mr Pearse's remarks were
general and long-term.
National Westminster and Lloyds also intimated they believed the days of
free banking in credit may be numbered.
'If only a small minority of your customers are paying bank charges, it's
something you look at,' an official at NatWest said.
Lloyds said UK customers with a current account took free banking for
granted but that Lloyds had more than 4m current account customers, of which
more than 70 per cent were effectively subsidised by the minority who became
overdrawn.
Paying their way, Page 6
Banker from the Old School, Page 34
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 14
</PAGE>
