FT  01 SEP 92 / London considers investor centre
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PLANS FOR a promotion centre to 'sell' London and act as a 'one-stop shop'
for potential investors are under consideration by three of the capital's
authorities.
The City Corporation, Westminster City Council and the Docklands Development
Corporation have commissioned Coopers &amp; Lybrand, the accountancy and
management consultancy firm, to report on the viability of such a centre.
The CBI is also closely involved in the project.
If Coopers reported favourably, the centre could be in operation by the
start of next year.
Premises have already been secured and a blueprint for an arms-length
company to run the centre, with a private-sector chief executive, has been
drawn up.
The centre is expected to cost about Pounds 700,000 a year, met largely by
the three authorities in the first year but with growing contributions from
businesses and other London authorities in later years.
The move would complement the planned London Business Forum, which the
government proposes to set up later this year, as promised in the
Conservative election manifesto.
Mr Michael Howard, the environment secretary, will soon appoint the forum's
chief executive - expected to be a prominent industrialist - and has been
engaged in talks with the three authorities to ensure they do not compete
for the same functions and private-sector funding.
Mr David Weeks, leader of Westminster City Council, said: 'A one-stop shop
ought to be a valuable commercial resource. Coopers are looking at investors
in London over the past four years, and those who, while interested, failed
to invest.'
He added: 'The centre would be plugged into everything, from the London
property market and development scene through to arts and architecture.'
The City Corporation is particularly keen on the promotion side, after the
success of its architectural exhibition at the Royal Exchange.
It believes that a London-wide body with a full-time secretariat could also
deflect criticism over the absence of a strategic authority in London.
Observer, Page 13
