FT  01 SEP 92 / Engineers warn on A-level courses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIXTH-form technology course in England and Wales are seriously inadequate
and needs to be reformed if the numbers of those proceeding to university
technology-based courses are not to continue declining, the Engineering
Council warns in a report published today.
It calls for technology A-level courses to be consistent with existing maths
and physics courses, and for a greater emphasis on practical application.
The report, written by Professor Alan Smithers of Manchester University, a
government curriculum adviser, says: 'The great difficulty with technology
at A-level is that hardly anyone seems to know what it is or how it is
expected to fit into the curriculum.'
It adds: 'It lacks any clear identity. Tortuous labels like Design and
Technology (Technology) and Design and Technology (Communication) not only
tend to get stuck on the tongue but leave the subjects largely unrecognised
in higher education.'
The council sets out an eight-point plan for reform.
