<HEADLINE>
FT  01 SEP 92 / CBI sees end to wage-price spiral
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN is in a strong position to break the wage-price spiral that has
undermined previous recoveries, according to the Confederation of British
Industry.
Mr Robbie Gilbert, CBI director of employment affairs, said yesterday that
only one-in-three UK employers was quoting the cost of living as an
important upward pressure on pay. During the past year one-in-four
settlements was at or below 3.5 per cent and a similar number between 3.5
per cent and 4.5 per cent.
He added that pay settlements were ahead of inflation as the UK entered the
recession and the latest evidence from the CBI's pay databank showed that
business factors were now the most important determinants of pay.
Yet Britain's two main independent pay research groups, Incomes Data
Services and Industrial Relations Services, both publish reports today
saying the link between pay and inflation remains central.
IDS says: 'Not only do most private-sector employers report that the rate of
change in the cost of living is a very important factor in decisions on pay,
but inflation protection is still quite explicitly built into a number of
major pay settlements'.
IRS has found that a majority of employers plan a further reduction in pay
rises in the next year.
A poll of 280 employers indicates that the average settlement will fall from
the current plateau of 4.3 per cent to between 3 per cent and 4 per cent.
About a quarter of employers plan to give the same rise as last year and
only one in 20 plans a pay freeze. The most important upward pressures on
pay are labour productivity and inflation.
IDS Report 624. Incomes Data Services, 193 St John Street, London EC1V 4LS.
IRS Pay and Benefits Bulletin. Industrial Relations Services, 18-20 Highbury
Place, London N5 1QP.
</TEXT>
